Dynamic Pathfinding Agent
What it does
Agent moves on a grid from a fixed start to a fixed goal using A* or GBFS. You can draw walls or
generate a random maze. In dynamic mode walls randomly spawn mid-run. If one blocks the path
the agent replans from its current position.
A*
f(n) = g(n) + h(n). Weighs both how far it's traveled and how far it has to go. Always finds the
shortest path. Slower than GBFS.
GBFS
f(n) = h(n) only. Ignores travel cost, just chases the goal greedily. Faster but the path it finds isn't
always the shortest.
Heuristics
Manhattan: |dr| + |dc|. Good fit for 4-directional grid movement. Euclidean: straight-line distance.
Slightly less accurate on a grid but still admissible.
Pros and Cons
A*
Pro: guaranteed shortest path. Con: slower, more memory, overkill on simple maps.
GBFS
Pro: fast, expands fewer nodes on clean maps. Con: no optimality guarantee, struggles in mazes.
Test Cases
A* best case
Empty grid, open path. Few nodes expanded, goes almost straight to goal.
A* worst case
Dense maze, goal tucked away. Explores most of the grid before getting through.
GBFS best case
Open grid, nothing in the way. Reaches goal faster than A* with fewer expansions.
GBFS worst case
Maze where the correct path goes away from the goal first. GBFS gets pulled the wrong way, ends
up with a longer path and more expansions than A*.
